This particular game is against a good friend

My opponent is a friend and I have often chastised him for getting his queen out too early. In this case I am threatening to gain material e.g. Bxc3+, bxc3, Qxb5


I also did it to tease him a little and to try to show that there are times when getting your queen out early isn't bad. In this case my queen is well supported and could prove time consuming to remove

Exchanges the bishop for my knight. I asked why he did this and he said that he sees knight as more of a threat. I think in a fairly open game like this one is so far that bishops are stronger.

I am also still threatening to gain material with Bxc3+, bxc3, Qxc3+
White has other options here that may be better. I was expecting Nge2 to protect the knight and allow white to castle, I think Qc2 is also playable

My development is now almost complete and I can castle if I choose, if white moves his G knight I am intending Ba6 to try to prevent him from castling

This is a very strange move as it not only weakens whites pawn structure, it prevents the g knight from developing to f2. The only purpose I can see that it might serve is to restrict my knight a little.

I'm now trying to work out how to exchange the white dsb and then how to attack the white e pawn
First lets get my king tucked away nice and safe
White can now castle if he chooses to the safety of the kings side
I am now back in a position where I can gain material Bxe2,Qxe2, Bxc3+, bxc3, Qxc3+ gains a pawn and a rook or prevent white from castling Bxe2, Kxe2
I think a better option might have been to castle
Now that white can't castle my rook is nicely lined up against his king
Pushes my queen away, Better may have been Nd3
Leaves my bishops unprotected however I am now looking to move my attack to the kings side by chasing off whites dsb with Nh5 and making use of the d8-h4 line with my queen
Pushes away my dsb
Allows me to advance my plans to remove whites dsb
